The recipe follows the Cookbook Mode structure established by Recipe 4.8 and contains:[0m[0m
- **The Problem**: Linda's case (six chronic conditions, post-CHF discharge) illustrating why static care plans fail[0m[0m
- **The Technology**: Goal-Action-Owner modeling, multi-condition reconciliation, therapeutic burden, goals-of-care alignment, and the load-bearing role of LLMs with strict constraints[0m[0m
- **General Architecture Pattern**: Seven-component pipeline (clinical content, inputs aggregation, goal derivation, action assembly + reconciliation, plan finalization, narrative + validation, feedback + adaptation) with ASCII diagrams[0m[0m
- **AWS Implementation**: Why-these-services rationale, Mermaid architecture diagram, full Prerequisites table, Ingredients table[0m[0m
- **Code (pseudocode)**: Six-step walkthrough plus the Python companion callout[0m[0m
- **Expected Results**: Sample plan record, sample patient narrative, sample clinician narrative, performance benchmarks table, where-it-struggles list[0m[0m
- **Why This Isn't Production-Ready**: Gap analysis with TODOs for the chapter-wide patterns (validator spec, identifier opacity, DLQ coverage, channel credentials, consent flow, regulatory analysis)[0m[0m
- **The Honest Take**: First-person engineer voice on the LLM-as-load-bearing trap, structured-then-narrative discipline, content/operations dominance over modeling, cohort fairness limits, and patient engagement reality[0m[0m
- **Variations**: 10 extensions including multi-language narratives, caregiver-facing variant, real-time RPM-driven adjustments, care-transition variants[0m[0m
- **Related Recipes**: Cross-references to all of 4.1 through 4.8 plus 4.10, 2.x, 7.x, 11.x, 12.x, 13.x[0m[0m
- **Additional Resources**: Verified AWS docs, three real aws-samples repos, FHIR/clinical references (POLST, Cumulative Complexity Model, STOPP/START, Beers, Obermeyer 2019)[0m[0m
- **Implementation Time**, [1mTags[22m, [1mNavigation[22m[0m[0m
